{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 15:24:10.906521", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nScope / summary\n- Topology: 3 OVS switches (spine_1, leaf_1, leaf_2) and hosts in 10.0.0.0/24. Management net 20.0.0.0/24 with controller at 20.0.0.100.\n- Symptom observed: L2/L3 connectivity between hosts on the same leaf is failing (example: host_1_1 cannot ping host_1_2). Many host-to-host reachability tests returned “unknown” or failed.\n- Primary finding: Leaf switches (leaf_1 and leaf_2) have their Open vSwitch datapath/bridge components effectively down (ovs-system / internal bridge ports are DOWN) while their physical interfaces show UP. The openvswitch-switch service on both leaf switches is inactive. This causes host-level connectivity on those leaves to fail despite management-plane connectivity to the controller being present.\n\nEvidence collected (commands and salient outputs)\n1) Failed ping between two hosts on the same leaf\n- From host_1_1 -> host_1_2:\n  - Ping output: “From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable” (5/5 packets lost)\n  - Interpretation: the host could not deliver/resolve L2 forwarding to the destination.\n\n2) Host interface / route correctness (hosts have correct IPs in 10.0.0.0/24)\n- host_1_1 ifconfig/ip addr:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (state UP)\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 route present\n- host_1_2 ifconfig/ip addr:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24 (state UP)\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 route present\n- Conclusion: host IP addresses and local kernel routes are correct; problem is not IP misconfiguration on hosts.\n\n3) Open vSwitch daemon status on leaf switches\n- systemctl status openvswitch-switch on leaf_1:\n  - Active: inactive (dead)\n- systemctl status openvswitch-switch on leaf_2:\n  - Active: inactive (dead)\n- Interpretation: the openvswitch-switch service is not running on both leaf devices.\n\n4) ip link / ovs-related link state on leaf switches\n- leaf_1 ip_addr shows many physical ethX interfaces present and UP (e.g., eth0..eth12 show UP and “master ovs-system”), but:\n  - ovs-system interface: state DOWN\n  - internal bridge interface (leaf_1): state DOWN\n- leaf_2: same condition — physical ports UP, but ovs-system and internal bridge device show DOWN.\n- Interpretation: the kernel datapath/bridge (ovs-system/internal) is down, so ports attached to it cannot forward L2 frames even though physical nic links are up.\n\n5) ovs-vsctl show and controller connectivity\n- ovs-vsctl show on spine_1, leaf_1, leaf_2: Bridges and controllers listed; controller reported as “is_connected: true” on those switches.\n- Observed inconsistency: controller connection appears established (management plane functional), yet OVS datapath/bridge is down on leaf switches.\n\n6) Spine switch\n- spine_1 shows management IP 20.0.0.1/24 and appears to have its bridge/datapath up (interfaces up) — spine seems healthy.\n\nLocalization — affected devices and scope\n- Primary faulty devices: leaf_1 and leaf_2 (both show openvswitch-switch.service inactive and ovs-system / internal bridge DOWN).\n- Impacted traffic:\n  - L2/L3 host-to-host traffic traversing leaf_1 and leaf_2 (intra-leaf and host-to-host across leaves) is impacted.\n  - Management-plane connectivity (20.0.0.0/24) between switches and controller appears functional — controller reported as connected to switches.\n  - spine_1 appears functional; problem localized to leaf switches’ OVS datapath.\n\nProbable root cause (most likely)\n- The Open vSwitch datapath/bridge (ovs-system/internal) on leaf switches is not active because the openvswitch-switch service is inactive (stopped/crashed/not started). This results in physical interfaces being up but not actually bridged (no L2 forwarding), so hosts connected to those leaf switches cannot reach each other at L2 (ARP resolution fails) and therefore ping fails.\n- Rationale:\n  - Hosts are correctly configured in 10.0.0.0/24 and are UP, yet pings return “Destination Host Unreachable” — consistent with missing L2 forwarding.\n  - ip link shows physical NICs enslaved to ovs-system but ovs-system is DOWN and the bridge internal port is DOWN.\n  - systemctl shows openvswitch-switch is inactive on both leaf devices.\n  - Controller connectivity being “is_connected: true” indicates the management/control channel is up but does not compensate for a disabled datapath on the leaf switches.\n\nAdditional observations and notes\n- There is an inconsistency to note: ovs-vsctl show reports bridges and shows controller connected, even while systemctl reports openvswitch-switch inactive and ovs-system DOWN. This could indicate partial components (e.g., ovsdb-server) are running or stale configuration is present but the kernel datapath or openvswitch switching agent is not operational. Regardless, the datapath is non-functional from a forwarding perspective.\n- Packet counters on hosts show many RX packets and very low TX for some hosts — could be background broadcast/management traffic being received on the physical NICs while host-originated L2 traffic fails to be forwarded.\n- Because both leaf switches show the same service inactive condition, the issue likely stems from those devices individually (e.g., OVS service failure) rather than an upstream topology problem.\n\nRecommended next verification steps (data collection only — no mitigation)\n- Confirm ovs kernel modules and ovs-vswitchd / ovsdb-server process statuses on leaf_1 and leaf_2 (ps, dmesg for OVS errors).\n- Check OVS logs on leaf_1 and leaf_2 (e.g., /var/log/openvswitch/* or system journal) to find service crash reasons.\n- Inspect ARP tables on hosts (arp -n) and check whether ARP requests are seen on the leaf interfaces (tcpdump on leaf physical ports).\n- Verify if any recent configuration change or package update occurred on the leaf switches that could have stopped the service.\n\nConclusion\n- Network is partially healthy: management plane and controller connectivity appear up; spine switch appears functional.\n- Critical anomaly: the Open vSwitch datapath/bridge on leaf_1 and leaf_2 is down / openvswitch-switch service inactive, causing L2 forwarding to fail and host-to-host connectivity to be broken on affected leaves.\n- Root cause (most likely): OVS service/datapath failure on leaf switches (leaf_1 and leaf_2).\n\nIf you want, I can run the additional verification commands (process list, journalctl, ovs logs, tcpdump, or ovs-related status) to gather the log evidence for the OVS service failure.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 26281, "output_tokens": 2660, "total_tokens": 28941, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 25728}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1152}}}
